2026-04-07

[current stage]
- Third `M1.4.2` implementation slice.
- Goal: add practical CSRF protection to the newly protected admin surface without rewriting all admin views into templates first.

[actions performed]
- Added session-backed admin CSRF token generation in `app/routes/auth.py`.
- Enforced CSRF validation for state-changing `/admin*` requests (`POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `DELETE`), accepting form field or `X-CSRF-Token`.
- Injected a hidden CSRF field into existing admin HTML forms automatically via response post-processing, so current inline-form pages remain functional during the transition period.
- Added `admin_csrf_token` fixture in `tests/conftest.py`.
- Updated admin POST tests to submit the explicit CSRF token.
- Added security tests proving:
  - admin POST without CSRF token is rejected,
  - admin HTML includes CSRF token injection.

[important commands]
- `sed -n '1,260p' app/routes/auth.py`
- `rg -n "method='post'|method=\"post\"|formmethod='post'|formmethod=\"post\"" app/routes/ops.py`
- `PYTHONPATH=. .venv/bin/pytest -q tests/test_ui_issues.py tests/test_ops_contracts.py tests/test_security.py`

[observations]
- Automatic CSRF field injection is a pragmatic bridge for the current inline-HTML admin UI. It is not the final shape, but it keeps the existing form-heavy screens working while the codebase is still mid-modularization.
- This slice materially improves the admin threat model without forcing the user model/RBAC work to land in the same commit.

[mistakes and lessons]
- One test method initially missed its `self` parameter inside a test class; the implementation was fine, the failure was test-shape only. When adding class-based pytest tests, verify method signatures before assuming runtime breakage.

[next planned implementation steps]
1. Decide whether the next `M1.4.2` slice should be stronger RBAC semantics or audit logging coverage.
2. If committing this slice, repeat the same branch-sync pattern only after the new `main` push succeeds.

